[[File:Jay Payton 2008.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Jay Payton]] was one of the first [[position player]]s to undergo the surgery twice.]]
[[File:John Smoltz with Colonel Air Force (cropped).jpg|thumb|150px|[[John Smoltz]] was the first pitcher who underwent the surgery to be elected to the Hall of Fame.]]
[[File:Jamie Moyer Phillies.JPG|thumb|150px|[[Jamie Moyer]] is the oldest player to undergo the surgery.]]
[[File:JVenters01.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Jonny Venters]] is perhaps the only player to undergo the surgery more than two times.]]
'''Tommy John surgery (TJS),''' known in [[medicine|medical]] [[medical practice|practice]] as '''ulnar collateral ligament''' ('''UCL''') '''reconstruction''', is a [[Graft (surgery)|surgical graft]] procedure in which the [[ulnar collateral ligament of elbow joint|ulnar collateral ligament]] in the [[Anatomical terms of location#Proximal and distal|medial]] [[Elbow-joint|elbow]] is replaced with either a [[tendon]] from elsewhere from the patient's own body, or the use of a tendon from the donated tissue from a [[cadaver]]. The procedure is common among collegiate and professional athletes in several sports, most notably [[baseball]].

The procedure was first performed in 1974 by orthopedic surgeon Dr. [[Frank Jobe]], then a [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] team physician. The surgery is named after [[Tommy John]], the first recipient of the surgery. John won 288 games in his career, which was extended by the surgery. Many players since have had Tommy John surgery.

