'''''Thermales''''' is an [[order (biology)|order]] of bacteria belonging to the [[Deinococcus–Thermus]] [[phylum]].<ref name="rainey">{{cite journal |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/9781118960608.obm00045/abstract |title=''Thermales'' ord. nov. |author1=Fred A. Rainey |author2=Milton S. da Costa |date=14 September 2015 |journal=Bergey's Manual of Systematics of Archaea and Bacteria |publisher=John Wiley and Sons, Inc. |doi=10.1002/9781118960608.obm00045 |accessdate=18 December 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218232014/http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/9781118960608.obm00045/abstract |archivedate=18 December 2016 |deadurl=no}}</ref> They are particularly resistant to heat, and live in the benthic zone of the Gulf of Mexico.<ref name="felder">{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CphA8hiwaFIC&pg=PA38&lpg=PA38&dq=%22thermales%22+bacteria&source=bl&ots=YjgVMJhQYN&sig=zpSrUoGt5cvd2RK3sCUIhE75CiA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiwj6ze7_7QAhWo1IMKHWSpB7cQ6AEINjAE#v=onepage&q=%22thermales%22%20bacteria&f=false |title=Gulf of Mexico Origin, Waters, and Biota: Biodiversity |editor1=John W. Tunnell, Jr. |editor2=Darryl L. Felder |editor3=Sylvia A. Earle |editor4=David K. Camp |publisher=[[Texas A&M University Press]] |page=38 |year=2009 |isbn=9781603442695 |accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref>

